'''''She Has a Name''''' is a play about [[human trafficking]] written by [[Andrew Kooman]] in 2009 as a one-act play and expanded to a full-length play in 2010. The play is about the [[trafficking of children]] into [[sexual slavery]] in order to [[Commercial sexual exploitation of children|exploit them commercially as prostitutes]] in the [[child sex tourism]] industry and was inspired by the deaths of 54 people in the [[Ranong human-trafficking incident]]. Kooman had previously published literature, but this was his first full-length play. The stage premiere of ''She Has a Name'' was directed by [[Stephen Waldschmidt]] at the [[EPCOR Centre for the Performing Arts]] in [[Calgary]], Alberta in February 2011. Performances ran from February 23 until March 12 in both Calgary and [[Red Deer, Alberta|Red Deer]], all of which sold out. From May to October 2012, ''She Has a Name'' [[2012 tour of She Has a Name|toured across Canada]]. In conjunction with the tour, [[A Better World]] raised money to help women and children who had been [[Human trafficking in Thailand|trafficked in Thailand]] as part of [[Prostitution in Thailand|the country's prostitution industry]]. After the Saturday matin<U+00E9>e in each city, there was a panel discussion to raise awareness about human trafficking.

Five actors portray ten characters. The two main characters are Jason, a young Canadian lawyer; and Number 18, a young female prostitute who claims to be fifteen years old and has been a prostitute for six years. The drama centers around Jason's infiltration of a brothel ring that is trafficking girls into [[Bangkok]]. Jason comes to believe that Number 18 could be a key witness to a human trafficking incident and tries to gain her trust and persuade her to testify against the ring. The victimized child in the play is known only by the number 18 to reflect that traffickers often dehumanize their victims by giving them a new name or simply a number, which in some cases is [[Human branding|branded]] onto the victim's body. Waldschmidt said he hoped that the play will educate Canadians about human trafficking and motivate them to act on what they learn, thereby turning them into [[Abolitionism#Contemporary abolitionism|contemporary abolitionists]].

The play received strong endorsement from Canadian [[Abolitionism|abolitionists]], including [[Member of Parliament (Canada)|MP]] [[Joy Smith]], [[Ratanak International]]'s [[Brian McConaghy]], and [[International Justice Mission|IJM]] Canada's [[Jamie McIntosh]]. The play's premiere and initial run were critically acclaimed. In the 2012 tour across Canada, the play was performed in several [[fringe theatre]] festivals, at which critics representing ''[[The Gazette (Montreal)|The Gazette]]'', the ''[[Winnipeg Free Press]]'', and [[CFEQ-FM]] said it stood out for its quality and moral content.

==Background==
[[Andrew Kooman]] first became aware of human trafficking while he was working for the nonprofit organization [[Youth With A Mission]] (YWAM)<ref name=Chronicle/> in southeast Malaysia,<ref name=Gazette>{{Cite journal|journal=[[The Gazette (Montreal)|The Gazette]]|title=Fringe 2012: Alberta group's play explores human trafficking|author=Pat Donnelly|date=June 15, 2012}}</ref> where he met child victims of human trafficking.<ref name=Chronicle>{{Cite journal|journal=[[The Chronicle Herald]]|title=Trafficked kids given identity: She Has a Name tells the story of child prostitute|author=Elissa Barnard|date=June 27, 2012|url=http://thechronicleherald.ca/artslife/111339-trafficked-kids-given-identity|accessdate=July 24, 2012}}</ref> Kooman later realized that human trafficking also occurs in Canada.<ref name=CKUA/> Kooman has spoken about cases where people have been trafficked into Calgary and Edmonton for prostitution, and said that sex workers may have been trafficked into Red Deer, his hometown, since it is also located along [[Alberta Highway 2]].<ref name=Advocate/> He started writing ''She Has a Name'' to bring attention to the issue of human trafficking, specifically in connection with sexual exploitation.<ref name=Advocate/>

After starting to write the play, Kooman read about the [[Ranong human-trafficking incident]] in which 121 people were trafficked from Burma to Thailand and left in a locked water tank, which was then abandoned by its drivers and was only discovered after 54 of the people had died from suffocation or [[hyperthermia]].<ref name=Bundle1>For the time of Kooman's reading about the incident, see {{Cite journal|journal=[[CFUV-FM]]|title=She Has a Name|url=http://cfuvfringefestival.wordpress.com/2012/08/23/she-has-a-name/|accessdate=August 24, 2012}}
*For the locations and number of victims involved in the incident, see {{Cite journal|journal=[[Red Deer Advocate]]|author=Susan Zielinski|title=Groups helping sex trade victims |date=September 21, 2012 |url = http://www.reddeeradvocate.com/news/local/Groups_helping_sex_trade_victims_170615546.html |accessdate = January 16, 2013}}
*For the type of container in which the victims were held, see {{Cite journal|title=Play personalizes an industry that strips away identity|journal=[[Red Deer Advocate]]|author=Lana Michelin|date=February 25, 2011|url=http://www.reddeeradvocate.com/entertainment/Play_personalizes_an_industry_that_strips_away_identity_116858973.html|accessdate=July 22, 2012}}
*For the number of victims who died in the incident, see {{Cite journal|journal=[[Gauntlet (newspaper)|Gauntlet]]|title=She Has a Name and a story, too: Theatre performance tours Canada to raise awareness about human trafficking in Southeast Asia|author=Pauline Anunciacion|date=February 16, 2012|url=http://www.thegauntlet.ca/story/she-has-name-and-story-too|accessdate=July 27, 2012}}
*For the assertion that victims died of suffocation, see {{Cite journal|journal=[[Times Colonist]]|author=Adrian Chamberlain|date=August 26, 2012|title=Fringe review: She Has a Name inspired by true story|url=http://www.timescolonist.com/news/Fringe+review+Name+inspired+true+story/7145452/story.html|accessdate=September 11, 2012}}
*For the assertion that victims died of hyperthermia, see {{Cite journal|journal=St. Albert Gazette|author=Anna Borowiecki|title=Play about human trafficking provides chilling insights|date=September 22, 2012|url=http://www.stalbertgazette.com/article/20120922/SAG0302/309229988/play-about-human-trafficking-provides-chilling-insights|accessdate=September 22, 2012}}
</ref> The truck carrying the water tank had been abandoned because it ran out of fuel.<ref name=Advocate>{{Cite journal|title=Play personalizes an industry that strips away identity|journal=[[Red Deer Advocate]]|author=Lana Michelin|date=February 25, 2011|url=http://www.reddeeradvocate.com/entertainment/Play_personalizes_an_industry_that_strips_away_identity_116858973.html|accessdate=July 22, 2012}}</ref> When the truck was discovered in April 2008, it contained men, women, and children.<ref name=Bundle2>For the time of the truck's discovery, see {{Cite journal|journal=[[London Free Press]]|title=Innocent victims at risk: Canadian play based on real-life human trafficking event|author=Joe Belanger|date=July 10, 2012|url=http://www.lfpress.com/entertainment/stage/2012/07/10/19972026.html|accessdate=July 25, 2012}}
*For the assertion that some of the victims were men and women, see {{Cite journal|journal=St. Albert Gazette|author=Anna Borowiecki|title=Play about human trafficking provides chilling insights|date=September 22, 2012|url=http://www.stalbertgazette.com/article/20120922/SAG0302/309229988/play-about-human-trafficking-provides-chilling-insights|accessdate=September 22, 2012}}
*For the assertion that some of the victims were children, see {{Cite journal|title=Play personalizes an industry that strips away identity|journal=[[Red Deer Advocate]]|author=Lana Michelin|date=February 25, 2011|url=http://www.reddeeradvocate.com/entertainment/Play_personalizes_an_industry_that_strips_away_identity_116858973.html|accessdate=July 22, 2012}}
</ref> Knowing that many of the impoverished girls who are smuggled in this manner become enslaved in brothels as [[Prostitution of children|child prostitutes]],<ref name=Review/> Kooman used the incident in the backstory of the play.<ref name=Gauntlet>{{Cite journal|journal=[[Gauntlet (newspaper)|Gauntlet]]|title=She Has a Name and a story, too: Theatre performance tours Canada to raise awareness about human trafficking in Southeast Asia|author=Pauline Anunciacion|date=February 16, 2012|url=http://www.thegauntlet.ca/story/she-has-name-and-story-too|accessdate=July 27, 2012}}</ref><ref name=Huntley>{{Cite video|people=Natalie Faith|title=She Has a Name|publisher=[[100 Huntley Street]]|date=June 27, 2012|url=http://www.100huntley.com/video?id=6VFfblaYp-k|accessdate=July 30, 2012}}</ref> To further ground the play in reality, Kooman researched human trafficking and met with survivors.<ref name=Examiner>{{Cite journal|journal=Edmonton Examiner|author=Aspen Gainer|title=Play about human trafficking, written by Albertan, comes to Edmonton|date=September 27, 2012|url=http://www.edmontonexaminer.com/2012/09/25/play-about-human-trafficking-written-by-albertan-comes-to-edmonton|accessdate=September 28, 2012}}</ref>

[[File:Andrew_Kooman.jpg|thumb|right|alt=A photograph of a man with brown eyes, brown hair, and dimples looking at the viewer and wearing a green sweater over a black shirt|''She Has a Name'' was [[Andrew Kooman]]'s debut play, but he had written non-theatrical literature beforehand, such as the [[Young-adult fiction|young-adult novel]] ''[[Ten Silver Coins|Ten Silver Coins: The Drylings of Acchora]]''.]]

Before writing ''She Has a Name'', Kooman had written other literary works, including the [[Young-adult fiction|young-adult novel]] ''[[Ten Silver Coins|Ten Silver Coins: The Drylings of Acchora]]'', and two plays, ''Shelter'' and ''Joseph'', that had been selected for development at [[Scripts At Work]] workshops.<ref name=PGC>{{cite web|title=PGC's Q&A with Andrew Kooman - Fringe Edition|publisher=[[Playwrights Guild of Canada]]|date=September 10, 2012|url=http://playwrightsguild.ca/news/pgcs-qa-andrew-kooman-fringe-edition|accessdate=September 11, 2012}}</ref> ''She Has a Name'' was his first full-length play.<ref name=Gazette/> Kooman started writing ''She Has a Name'' in 2008<ref name=Weber>{{Cite journal|journal=Red Deer Express|author=Mark Weber|title=Acclaimed local playwright wraps successful tour|date=September 26, 2012|url=http://www.reddeerexpress.com/news/Acclaimed_local_playwright_wraps_successful_tour_171342971.html|accessdate=September 30, 2012}}</ref> and finished a one-act version by 2009,<ref name=Express>{{Cite journal|title=Local author unveils adventurous and original tale|author=Mark Weber|journal=Red Deer Express|date=December 9, 2009}}</ref> writing under the guidance of a [[dramaturge]] at a Scripts At Work workshop<ref name=Advocate/> at Red Deer College.<ref name=Michelin>{{Cite journal|journal = [[Red Deer Advocate]]|author = Lara Michelin|title = Powerful play returning home|date=September 24, 2012|url = http://www.reddeeradvocate.com/entertainment/local/Powerful_play_returning_home_171009181.html
|accessdate = January 16, 2013}}{{subscription}}</ref> Kooman drew on his experiences working with a Canadian film crew in Thailand in 2006.<ref name=Radio/> He intended to extend the one-act version to a full-length play eventually.<ref name=Advocate/>

In January 2010, there was a full reading of the one-act version of the play. Despite an unfinished script and a performance by amateur actors, the reading evoked a strong response from the audience.<ref name=Project>{{Cite journal|journal=The Calgary Journal|title=Human trafficking portrayed through local theatre project: World premiere of 'She Has A Name' in Calgary on Feb. 23|author=James Wilt|date=February 4, 2011|url=http://www.calgaryjournalonline.ca/september-print-issue/arts-a-entertainment/1719-human-trafficking-portrayed-through-local-theatre-project|accessdate=August 14, 2012}}</ref> This reading was presented at a justice conference in [[Grand Rapids, Michigan]].<ref name=Radio>{{cite web|author=Kathleen Renne|publisher=CKUA Radio Network|title=February 27, 2011|date=February 27, 2011|url=http://www.ckua.com/pages/landing?blockID=428105|accessdate=July 30, 2012}}</ref> After doing a presentation about human trafficking in [[Strathmore, Alberta|Strathmore]], Kooman was approached by [[Stephen Waldschmidt]], one of Burnt Thicket Theatre's artistic associates.<ref name=Gazette/> Waldschmidt asked Kooman for permission to read the script of ''She Has a Name'';<ref name=Gazette/> Waldschmidt said that it was one of two scripts that he could not put down before finishing.<ref name=Project/> Waldschmidt initially distanced himself from the play because of the immensity and ugliness of the issue, but he and Kooman later expanded the script to a full-length play with an extra hour of material by the end of 2010,<ref name=Advocate/> resulting in a play that can be performed in 90 minutes<ref name=Plank/> but may last up to two hours.<ref name=Victoria>{{Cite journal|journal=Victoria News|title=Moving play, She Has a Name, comes with a message|date=February 16, 2012|url=http://www.vicnews.com/entertainment/139460168.html|accessdate=July 26, 2012}}</ref> Waldschmidt directed the play's premiere, and Burnt Thicket Theatre served as the play's initial production company.<ref name=Advocate/>

==Productions==
===Initial run===
[[File:She Has a Name 2011 - Grooming.jpg|thumb|alt=A photograph of five people, four of which are women, the rightmost three of whom are wearing white cloaks and the remaining woman being embraced by the man|The 2011 cast (left to right: [[Denise Wong]], [[Aaron Krogman]], [[Cari Russell]], [[Glenda Warkentin]], [[Sienna Howell-Holden]])]]

The stage premiere of ''She Has a Name'' was directed by Stephen Waldschmidt,<ref name=Strathmore/> who was also the [[scenic design]]er.<ref name=Standard/> Auditions for the play were held on September 13, 14, and 15, 2010.<ref name=Audition/> [[Aaron Krogman]] was selected to portray Jason and the unnamed pimp, [[Sienna Howell-Holden]] to portray Mama, [[Glenda Warkentin]] to portray Marta,<ref name=Sun>{{Cite journal|journal=[[Calgary Sun]]|title=Calgary's She Has a Name a 'heart-wrenching' hit|author=Louis Hobson|date=February 24, 2011|url=http://www.calgarysun.com/entertainment/columnists/louis_hobson/2011/02/24/17398956.html|accessdate=July 22, 2012}}</ref> [[Denise Wong]] to portray Number 18, and [[Cari Russell]] to portray Ali. Both Wong and Russell said they become more emotionally involved in the play than they had originally anticipated,<ref name=Fast>{{Cite journal|journal=[[Fast Forward Weekly]]|date=February 17, 2011|author=Krista Sylvester|accessdate=July 21, 2012|title=They all have a name|url=http://www.ffwdweekly.com/article/arts/theatre/they-all-have-a-name-7022/}}</ref> Howell-Holden said that the play changed her life,<ref name=Global>{{Cite journal|journal=[[CFSK-DT]]|title=She has a Name: Inspired by a 2008 event, a new compelling play now running in Saskatoon gives a face to human trafficking|url=http://www.globalsaskatoon.com/video/she+has+a+name/video.html?v=2241339591&p=1&s=dd#video|accessdate=July 28, 2012}}</ref> and Warkentin found acting in the play an emotional challenge<ref name=Powerful>{{Cite journal|journal=[[Lethbridge Herald]]|author=Lacey Vornbrock|title=Powerful play hits city stage|date=May 23, 2012}}</ref> and said that she did not realize the depth of the problem of human trafficking.<ref name=Beat>{{Cite journal|journal=L.A. Beat|title=Glenda Warkentin returns home to perform She Has A Name|author=Richard Amery|date=May 18, 2012|url=http://labeat.ca/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=2166:glenda-warkentin-returns-home-to-perform-she-has-a-name&catid=34:drama-latest&Itemid=58
|accessdate=July 27, 2012}}</ref> Waldschmidt suggested that Warkentin audition for the play after seeing her perform at [[Rosebud Theatre]] in Rosebud, Alberta.<ref name=Lethbridge>{{Cite journal|journal=[[Lethbridge Herald]]|author=Al Beeber|date=May 11, 2012|title=She has a name}}</ref> Wong, Krogman, and Kooman spoke highly of Waldschmidt's directing, and Kooman praised Waldschmidt's work as scenic designer.<ref name=Standard/> Waldschmidt praised the cast's acting.<ref name=CFUV>{{Cite journal|journal=[[CFUV-FM]]|title=She Has a Name|url=http://cfuvfringefestival.wordpress.com/2012/08/23/she-has-a-name/|accessdate=August 24, 2012}}</ref> He said he found the play's opening scene, in which a rape occurs, the most difficult to stage, despite having previously performed a similar rape scene as an actor.<ref name=Project/> The premiere of ''She Has a Name'' was produced by Burnt Thicket Theatre in partnership with Raise Their Voice.<ref name=Charlebois>{{Cite journal|journal=The Charlebois Post|title=Event: She Has a Name (Fringe)|date=June 12, 2012|url=http://www.charpo-montreal.com/2012/06/event-she-has-name-fringe.html|accessdate=July 24, 2012}}</ref><ref name=Sunrise>{{Cite journal|journal=Country Sunrise News|title=Locally Grown Play She Has a Name|volume=15|issue=3|date=April 2012}}</ref> The office of [[Joy Smith]], MP for [[Kildonan<U+2014>St. Paul]],<ref name=Press>{{Cite journal|title=Burnt Thicket Theatre presents She Has A Name by Andrew Kooman|journal=[[Winnipeg Free Press]]|url=http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/arts-and-life/events/161478665.html|accessdate=August 24, 2012}}</ref> released a statement advertising the premiere of ''She Has a Name''.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=Hope for the Sold|author=Michelle Brock|title=She Has a Name: A Play About Human Trafficking|date=February 25, 2011|url=http://hopeforthesold.com/she-has-a-name-a-play-about-human-trafficking/|accessdate=August 24, 2012}}</ref>

The troupe rehearsed for three weeks in Strathmore before the premiere,<ref name=Standard>{{Cite journal|journal = The Strathmore Standard|title = Local church hosts world-class rehersals (sic)|author = Sara Wilson|date=February 22, 2011}}</ref> which was performed at the [[EPCOR Centre for the Performing Arts]] in Calgary in February 2011.<ref name=Strathmore>{{Cite journal|title = Local director shines light on global crisis|author = Sara Wilson|journal = The Strathmore Standard|date = January 12, 2011}}</ref> Performances ran on the centre's Motel stage<ref name=Reflector>{{cite web|title=Raise the curtain on a new year of theatre|author=Kevin Rushworth|date=January 19, 2011|publisher=The Reflector|url=http://www.thereflector.ca/2011/01/19/raise-the-curtain-on-a-new-year-of-theatre/|accessdate=July 21, 2012}}</ref> between February 23 and March 5.<ref name=Strathmore/> Tickets were quickly sold out,<ref name=Times>{{Cite journal|date=March 18, 2011|journal=Strathmore Times|title=She has a name|author=Shannon LeClair|url=http://strathmoretimes.com/March-18-2011-Strathmore-Times/she-has-a-name.html|accessdate=July 23, 2012}}</ref> and people wanting to buy tickets at the door, sometimes numbering 20 or 30,<ref name=Playwright>{{Cite journal|journal=[[Red Deer Advocate]]|author=Lana Michelin|date=May 15, 2012|title=Playwright tells story of human trafficking |url = http://www.reddeeradvocate.com/entertainment/local/Playwright_tells_story_of_human_trafficking_151546395.html|accessdate = January 16, 2013}}{{subscription}}</ref> had to be turned away.<ref name=Gazette/> Four days after the premiere, Burnt Thicket Theatre moved the play to the [[Scott Block Theatre]] in Red Deer, where the play was performed until March 12.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Human Trafficking - Joy's HT Updates - February 2011 Update|publisher=[[Joy Smith]]|year=2011|url=http://www.joysmith.ca/main.asp?fxoid=FXMenu,3&cat_ID=27&sub_ID=106&sub2_ID=40|accessdate=November 11, 2012|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20110722154456/http://www.joysmith.ca/main.asp?fxoid=FXMenu,3&cat_ID=27&sub_ID=106&sub2_ID=40|archivedate=July 22, 2011}}</ref> All the performances in Red Deer were sold out.<ref name=Sunrise/> The play drew an emotional reaction from the audience.<ref name=Gauntlet/><ref name=Justice>{{cite web|publisher=[[International Justice Mission]]|title=Play exposes realities of human trafficking|date=May 30, 2012|url=http://www.ijm.ca/news/News/437|accessdate=July 27, 2012}}</ref> The most common audience responses were sadness and gratitude.<ref name=Huntley/> Kooman was told that many of the audience members at the initial performances later responded to the play by talking with others about human trafficking, writing letters to their Members of Parliament, and doing other creative things on the subject.<ref name=Justice/> They also contacted Waldschmidt, sometimes up to a year later, with stories about how the play had continued to affect their lives.<ref name=Huntley/> In conjunction with the initial run of ''She Has a Name'', Burnt Thicket Theatre provided the names of [[List of organizations opposing human trafficking|organizations that assist human-trafficking victims]].<ref name=Advocate/> There was also a panel discussion about human trafficking after the matin<U+00E9>e on February 26.<ref name=Times/>

[[File:She Has a Name 2012 - Conflict.jpg|thumb|alt=A photograph of a man and a woman, both wearing dress shirts and jeans, the woman also wearing a necklace and a watch, all in front of a painted backdrop|[[Andrew Kooman]] made several changes to the script of ''She Has a Name'' after the premiere, such as making the interactions between Jason and Marta more dynamic.]]

After the play's initial run, Kooman revised the script,<ref name=Beat/> making prominent changes in the scenes involving Jason and Marta.<ref name=Playwright/> In the version performed at the premiere, the two characters debate issues of human rights on a solely philosophical level, while in the new version, Marta makes real demands of Jason,<ref name=Michelin/> making their interactions more dynamic.<ref name=Playwright/> Kooman made Jason's wife Ali more patient and understanding in dealing with Jason's lengthy absences from home<ref name=Lana/> and removed the [[intermission]].<ref name=Michelin/> According to reviewer Lana Michelin of the ''[[Red Deer Advocate]]'', Kooman's changes strengthened the emotional pull of the play.<ref name=Playwright/><ref name=Lana>{{Cite journal|journal=[[Red Deer Advocate]]|author=Lana Michelin|date=October 4, 2012|title=She Has A Name returns with more emotional punch|url = http://www.reddeeradvocate.com/entertainment/local/She_Has_A_Name_returns_with_more_emotional_punch_172677831.html|accessdate = January 16, 2013}}{{subscription}}</ref> Because of the amount of interest in ''She Has a Name'' in 2011, not enough tickets were available for the initial run, and a second run in the fall of 2011 was planned.<ref name=Gazette/><ref name=Radio/> In order to finance a tour of the play, Burnt Thicket Theatre raised money through fundraisers,<ref name=Journal/> which included the 2011 Calgary [[Ride for Refuge]].<ref name=Journal>{{Cite journal|journal=The Calgary Journal|title=Ride for Refuge bike ride raises money to end sex trafficking: Organizer says event exceeded expectations|author=James Wilt|date=October 18, 2011|url=http://www.calgaryjournal.ca/index.php/ourcity/news/175-ride-for-refuge-bike-ride-raises-money-to-end-sex-trafficking|accessdate=July 26, 2012}}</ref><ref name=Cowley>{{Cite journal |journal=[[Red Deer Advocate]] |author=Paul Cowley |title='Power of hope' helps save child from sexual exploitation |date=October 9, 2012 |url = http://www.reddeeradvocate.com/news/local/Power_of_hope_helps_save_child_from_sexual_exploitation_173286971.html|accessdate = January 16, 2013}}{{subscription}}</ref> In August 2011, extracts from ''She Has a Name'' were read at a conference in Strathmore called Justice Tapestry.<ref name=Anchor>{{Cite journal|journal=The Anchor Weekly|title=Conference Aims To Expose The Realities Of Human Trafficking: Justice Tapestry Using Art To Inspire An End To Exploitation|author=Rachael Frey|date=August 10, 2011|url=http://www.theanchor.ca/2011/conference-aims-to-expose-the-realities-of-human-trafficking/|accessdate=July 23, 2012}}</ref>

By February 2012, Kooman was working on a screenplay version of ''She Has a Name''.<ref name=Gauntlet/> The idea of a [[stage-to-film adaptation]] of ''She Has a Name'' was also independently suggested by Pat Donnelly of ''[[The Gazette (Montreal)|The Gazette]]''.<ref name=Fringe>{{Cite journal|title=Montreal Fringe Festival: No Fixed Abode, She Has a Name, The Harvester|journal=[[The Gazette (Montreal)|The Gazette]]|author=Pat Donnelly|date=June 17, 2012|url=http://blogs.montrealgazette.com/2012/06/17/montreal-fringe-festival-no-fixed-abode-she-has-a-name-the-harvester/|accessdate=July 31, 2012}}</ref> A staged reading of the play took place at Mount Royal University on February 16.<ref name=Canadian>{{cite news|date=February 16, 2012|author=Frank Rackow|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]|title=She Has A Name|url=http://www.cbc.ca/homestretch/episode/2012/02/16/she-has-a-name/|accessdate=August 1, 2012}}</ref>

===2012 tour===
{{main|2012 tour of She Has a Name}}
[[File:She Has a Name 2012 - Death.jpg|thumb|right|alt=A photograph of five people, four of whom are women in white cloaks and the other of whom is a man wearing a dress shirt over a black shirt|The 2012 cast (left to right: [[Sienna Howell-Holden]], [[Glenda Warkentin]], [[Denise Wong]], [[Carl Kennedy]], [[Alysa van Haastert]])]]

The 2012 tour of ''She Has a Name'' was a [[fringe theatre]] tour across Canada.<ref>{{Cite journal|journal=[[Calgary Herald]]|author=Bob Clark|coauthor=Stephen Hunt|date=August 2, 2012|title=Fringe Picks: Eight shows that caught our attention|url=http://www.calgaryherald.com/entertainment/Fringe+Picks+Eight+shows+that+caught+attention/7033631/story.html|accessdate=August 3, 2012}}</ref> The performances were co-produced by Burnt Thicket Theatre and Raise Their Voice<ref name=Herald>{{Cite journal|journal=[[Calgary Herald]]|title=She Has a Name to tour Canada|date=April 6, 2012}}</ref> and were directed by Stephen Waldschmidt.<ref name=Charlebois/> [[Carl Kennedy]] portrayed Jason, [[Evelyn Chew]] portrayed Number 18, [[Alysa van Haastert]] portrayed Ali, Warkentin returned to portray Marta, and Howell-Holden returned to portray Mama.<ref name=Nicholls/> Despite the fact that ''She Has a Name'' is set in Southeast Asia, the producers deliberately cast actors who were not of Asian descent to avoid giving the impression that human trafficking is limited to Asia.<ref name=Gauntlet/> The tour started on May 23 in [[Lethbridge]] and went on to [[Saskatoon]], [[Ottawa]], [[Montreal]], [[Halifax Regional Municipality|Halifax]],<ref name=Herald/> [[London, Ontario|London]],<ref name=London>{{Cite journal|journal=[[London Free Press]]|title=Innocent victims at risk: Canadian play based on real-life human trafficking event|author=Joe Belanger|date=July 10, 2012|url=http://www.lfpress.com/entertainment/stage/2012/07/10/19972026.html|accessdate=July 25, 2012}}</ref> [[Winnipeg]],<ref name=Winnipeg>{{Cite journal|journal=[[Winnipeg Free Press]]|author=Kevin Prokosh|title=She Has a Name|date=July 17, 2012|url=http://www.winnipegfreepress.com/special/fringe/reviews/She-Has-a-Name-162130445.html?viewAllComments=y|accessdate=July 28, 2012}}</ref> Calgary,<ref name=Review/> [[Victoria, British Columbia|Victoria]],<ref name=Festival>{{cite web|title=Pick of the Fringe!|date=September 3, 2012|publisher=[[Intrepid Theatre#Victoria Fringe Theatre Festival|Victoria Fringe Theatre Festival]]|url=http://www.victoriafringe.com/blog/pick-of-the-fringe/|accessdate=September 11, 2012}}</ref> Vancouver,<ref name=Plays>{{Cite journal|journal=Vancouverplays.com|date=August 2012|volume=98|title=She Has a Name|url=http://www.vancouverplays.com/theatre/previews_theatre/preview_fringe_12_she_has_a_name.shtml|accessdate=September 11, 2012}}</ref> [[Kelowna]],<ref name=Kelowna>{{Cite journal|journal=Kelowna Capital News|date=September 17, 2012|title=Award-winning play coming to Kelowna|url=http://www.kelownacapnews.com/entertainment/170109746.html|accessdate=September 18, 2012}}</ref> Edmonton,<ref name=Nicholls>{{Cite journal|journal=[[Edmonton Journal]]|author=Liz Nicholls|title=Theatre review: Performances outshine writing in vivid activist play|date=September 26, 2012}}</ref> and Red Deer.<ref name=Charlebois/><ref name=Weber/>

After the Saturday matin<U+00E9>e in each city,<ref name=Returns>{{Cite journal|title=She Has A Name returns |author=Shannon LeClair |date=April 20, 2012 |journal=Strathmore Times |url=http://www.strathmoretimes.com/April-20-2012-Strathmore-Times/she-has-a-name-returns.html |accessdate=July 30, 2012}}</ref> a panel discussion was held with both the audience and non-audience members. The purpose of these discussions was to raise awareness about human trafficking in Canada and elsewhere.<ref name=Michelin/> Human trafficking expert panel members included [[Brian McConaghy]], founder of Ratanak International;<ref name=Press/> [[Trisha Baptie]], a founding member of [[EVE (organization)|EVE]] and a member of the [[Office to Combat Trafficking in Persons]] (OCTIP);<ref name=Plank/> and [[Glendene Grant]], founder of Mothers Against Trafficking in Humans.<ref name=Church>{{cite web|title='She Has A Name' Production|date=September 10, 2012|publisher=New Life Church|url=http://newlife.bc.ca/2012/09/she-has-a-name-production/|accessdate=October 3, 2012}}</ref> [[A Better World]] (ABW) partnered with Raise Their Voice to raise funds throughout the tour to help women and children who had been [[Human trafficking in Thailand|trafficked in Thailand]] as part of [[Prostitution in Thailand|the country's prostitution industry]].<ref name=Zielinski>{{Cite journal|journal=[[Red Deer Advocate]]|author=Susan Zielinski|title=Groups helping sex trade victims |date=September 21, 2012 |url = http://www.reddeeradvocate.com/news/local/Groups_helping_sex_trade_victims_170615546.html |accessdate = January 16, 2013}}{{subscription}}</ref> Kooman stated that he had "a 'pinch me' sort of feeling that [the 2012 tour] has happened, and that there is interest beyond this tour".<ref name=Weber/>

==Characters==
[[File:She Has a Name 2011 - Voices.jpg|thumb|alt=A photograph of a kneeling woman wearing a jean skirt surrounded by three other women in white cloaks staring at her all in front of a painted backdrop|The voices have been variously considered [[angel]]s or ghosts, and are sometimes frightening and at other times consoling.]]

While there are ten different characters in the play, the script calls for only five actors:<ref name=Fast/> four females and one male.<ref name=Audition>{{cite web|publisher=Calgary Arts Development|title=Audition Notice - She Has A Name|author=James Popoff|date=August 24, 2010|url=http://www.calgaryartsdevelopment.com/content/audition-notice-she-has-name|accessdate=August 3, 2012}}</ref> The play's main characters are Jason and Number 18. Jason is a young, Canadian lawyer with experience in corporate law. He found this work unsatisfying, so he started working in international human rights law for the United Nations and a non-governmental organization (NGO) that opposes sex trafficking. Number 18{{mdash}}the play's heroine{{mdash}}is a young, female prostitute who claims to be fifteen years old and has been a prostitute for six years. Ali is Jason's beautiful wife, and the couple have two young daughters. Marta is Jason's employer, who has become very tough from years of fighting for justice and who is now driven and stressed. The other characters are an unnamed pimp and Mama, his assistant who is a cruel [[mama-san|brothel keeper]].

Both of the male characters{{mdash}}Jason and the pimp{{mdash}}are played by the same actor.<ref name=Calgary>{{Cite journal|journal=[[Calgary Sun]]|author=Louis Hobson|date=May 4, 2012|title=Actor makes Name in trafficking play|url=http://www.calgarysun.com/2012/05/04/actor-makes-name-in-trafficking-play|accessdate=July 30, 2012}}</ref> Jason and Number 18 are haunted by the voices of four female sex slaves who have died. As poetic and prophetic voices, these characters serve much the same purpose as a [[Greek chorus]] in [[Greek tragedy|Greek tragedies]].<ref name=Advocate/> Variously considered angels<ref name=Uptown>{{Cite journal|journal=[[Uptown (newspaper)|Uptown]]|date=July 21, 2012|title=Winnipeg Fringe Theatre Festival 2012 reviews |url=http://www.uptownmag.com/arts/features/WINNIPEG-FRINGE-THEATRE-FESTIVAL-REVIEWS-163282806.html|accessdate=July 28, 2012}}</ref> or ghosts,<ref name=Preachy/> the voices are played by the female actors who portray Number 18, Marta, Ali, and Mama.<ref name=Nicholls/> While these voices emphasize the horrors of the sex industry, they also empower Number 18, comforting her as divine messengers. The fact that the chorus is made up of dead child prostitutes is revealed only at the end of the play.

==Plot summary==
[[File:She Has a Name 2012 - Pimp.jpg|thumb|250px|alt=A photograph of five people, three of whom are wearing white cloaks, one of whom is wearing a red shirt, and the remaining one of whom is holding a gun|Number 18 is regularly abused despite being her pimp's favourite prostitute.]]

In a bar, Number 18 is being raped by a pimp who then makes her his sex slave. Number 18's father died while she was still young, and her family found it difficult to support her. Strangers took her from her home in Cambodia, replaced her name with a number, and used her as a child prostitute, moving her between countries and prostituting her. Number 18 eventually ends up in the [[Child prostitution in Thailand|Thai child prostitution industry]]. Number 18 services mostly rich men, many of whom are foreign tourists. In a brothel and bar called The Pearl, Number 18 is kept in a dark room containing only a table and a dilapidated bed. Whenever she fails to follow the orders of Mama, the brothel-keeper, Mama shouts at her and beats her. Number 18 prays that a man will eventually come to save her from these circumstances. At the same time, she has become the most elegant and highly sought-after prostitute at The Pearl and is her pimp's favourite worker. While she has become very knowledgeable about and proficient in pleasing men sexually, she is also childlike and dries her face with her skirt and plays with its hem.

Jason has left his wife and children in Canada, a high-paying job and a career path that could have led to a partnership at his father-in-law's law firm to start working with an NGO in Thailand. Jason's first task is to find witnesses to or survivors from a human-trafficking incident and to then shut down the brothels into which they have been trafficked. Jason's boss, Marta, sends him into the brothels because she cannot go in herself. Jason's wife Ali communicates with him over [[Skype]].

As he infiltrates an Asia-wide brothel ring, Jason's specific focus is the ring's trafficking of girls into Bangkok, where the brothels prostitute them through the child sex tourism industry. An abandoned storage truck containing the bodies of dead sex workers has been discovered. Jason is trying to build a legal case against the brothel ring. He pays to see various prostitutes hoping that one of them witnessed the incident. The first prostitute he visits is Number 18, and he is very nervous. Number 18 is very attractive and ready to please, and she tries to seduce Jason. Jason does not want the [[girlfriend experience]], and thinks that she could be a key witness, so he tries to gain her trust and persuade her to testify against the ring. The other captives in the brothels Jason infiltrates are too afraid to testify in the case. Number 18 consents to answer some of Jason's questions about where she is from, where she has worked, and how long she has been working, but she only agrees to answer these questions if Jason is willing to pay her 100 [[Thai baht|baht]] for each response. She reveals that she has been prostituted in brothels in Thailand and Malaysia.

[[File:She Has a Name 2011 - Death.jpg|thumb|right|alt=A photograph of four people, the leftmost three of whom are women wearing white cloaks and the remaining person being a kneeling man|Ultimately, the characters are trapped in a [[no-win situation]], and the play ends in catastrophe.]]

Number 18 turns out to be one of the girls who were trafficked in the storage truck, but she escaped and ended up at The Pearl. Number 18 is traumatized and does not understand what Jason wants. Testifying against the ring would endanger her life; every girl who has talked about the storage truck incident has been killed. Her first reaction to Jason's questions is to try to silence him and get him to leave. One night, Number 18 is injured in a party at the brothel and is barely able to walk when Jason visits her. When he tells Ali about his experiences, she begs him to return to Canada. However, Jason believes that he is in Bangkok by [[divine providence]]. Once Number 18 understands that Jason is unlike the other men who frequent The Pearl, she learns to trust him as a friend, agrees to testify against the brothel ring, and is willing to be rescued. Jason's next challenge is to rescue her from The Pearl. He pays the Number 18's pimp enough money to take her away from the brothel for a weekend. In the meantime, Mama finds and confiscates the baht Jason had paid Number 18; Mama then correctly suspects that the weekend Jason has paid for is a trick. When Jason arrives to pick up Number 18, Mama tells him Number 18 has died and offers him a refund. Not believing that Number 18 is dead, Jason resorts to violence and Mama mocks him for being part of the rich Western culture that is responsible for members of the [[Third World]] becoming victims of sex trafficking. Jason stops short of hurting Mama and leaves the brothel, going to tell Marta what happened. Marta, through her network of connections, discovers that Number 18 is still alive. Although she sees Number 18 as evidence rather than as a person, Marta steps in and risks her life for Number 18, posing as a lawyer protecting Number 18's rights. The pimp is not fooled, and he threatens Marta with a gun, forcing her to leave the area. Jason manages to make his way to Number 18, but the pimp kills her before Jason is able to rescue her. Number 18 then joins the chorus of dead child prostitutes who have been watching over and commenting on all of the events up until this point.

==Themes==
[[File:Stephen_Waldschmidt.jpg|thumb|alt=A photograph of a man with blue-green eyes looking at the viewer, smiling, and wearing a brown shirt all in front of a sheet of black material|[[Stephen Waldschmidt]] said that the sympathetic portrayal of the perpetrators prevents the play from becoming simplistic.]]

Kooman made justice the focus of ''She Has a Name'';<ref>{{Cite journal|title=living an 'Ah Ha' moment|author=Lani Ledingham|journal=[[Red Deer College]] Notebook|date=October 2010|url=http://my.texterity.com/notebook/note2010fall?sub_id=Rjp3BhSqrYso#pg13|accessdate=July 21, 2012}}</ref> the social issues that interest him include poverty, the [[Epidemiology of HIV/AIDS|HIV/AIDS epidemic]], and the [[effects of war]].<ref name=Weber/> The central issues in ''She Has a Name'' are gender-based.<ref name=Gazette/> The general topic of the play is human trafficking,<ref name=Strathmore/> and specifically the trafficking of children into sexual slavery in order to exploit them commercially as prostitutes in the child sex tourism industry.<ref name=Sun/> Kooman has stated that ''She Has a Name'' "suggests that justice can only be realized if real people know, care and take informed and decisive action".<ref name=Fast/> The victimized child in the play is known only by the number 18 to reflect that traffickers often dehumanize their victims by giving them a new name or simply a number, which in some cases is [[Human branding|branded]] onto the victim's body.<ref name=Community/> After his rape of Number 18, the pimp leaves the situation without averse effect, but Number 18 is left bleeding from her crotch and her mouth, and she experiences fear, anger, and shame.<ref name=Anna>{{Cite journal|journal=St. Albert Gazette|author=Anna Borowiecki|title=Humanity<U+2019>s ugliness exposed in She Has A Name: Show about sex trade is gut-wrenching, disturbing|date=September 27, 2012|url=http://www.stalbertgazette.com/article/20120927/SAG0302/309279998/humanity-s-ugliness-exposed-in-she-has-a-name|accessdate=October 1, 2012}}</ref> The play invites viewers to feel sympathetic towards Number 18,<ref name=Victoria/> and while the world of human trafficking is depicted as horrific and ugly,<ref name=CKUA>{{cite web|title=Tuesday, February 22, 2011|publisher=[[CKUA Radio Network]]|author=Kathleen Renne|date=February 22, 2011|url=http://www.ckua.com/02/22/11/Tuesday-February-22-2011/landing.html?blockID=415499&feedID=7643|accessdate=July 22, 2012}}</ref> both the victims and perpetrators of human trafficking are portrayed as relatable characters,<ref name=Fast/> suggesting that every individual has inherent value and dignity.<ref name=Gauntlet/> Waldschmidt said that the sympathetic portrayal of the perpetrators prevents the play from becoming a simplistic story of good and evil.<ref name=Project/> According to Liz Nicholls of the ''[[Edmonton Journal]]'', Number 18 is a nuanced character, better-developed than the stock [[damsel in distress]] character.<ref name=Nicholls/>

[[File:She Has a Name 2012 - Skype.jpg|thumb|left|300px|alt=A photograph of a man wearing a dress shirt and blue jeans standing and leaning on a table opposite a blonde woman in a green dress|In order to depict the tension between Jason and Ali, the two communicate via [[Skype]], which is represented on stage by two laptops that are set up back-to-back.]]

Kooman said that the massive proportions of human trafficking often prevent people from dealing with it; he therefore chose to portray a single trafficked victim in the play so that audiences could approach the subject on a more workable level.<ref name=Advocate/> He hoped that audiences would avoid getting stuck in the statistics of human trafficking and would connect with a personal story.<ref name=Anchor/> The two questions that propel the story are: "Can [Jason] convince [Number 18] to risk her life to testify for the sake of justice?" and "Can he save her from the unthinkable circumstances?".<ref name=PGC/> Jason is weary and,<ref name=Sun/> while he never falls into self-pity,<ref name=Lana/> he comes to hate himself for his inability to save Number 18 from her slavery<ref name=Sun/> because he lacks the evidence he requires for his case to be successful in court.<ref name=Lana/> Much of the play is concerned with demonstrating the immensity of the difficulties that face Jason in trying to rescue Number 18.<ref name=Nicholls/> For example, he finds it difficult to be away from his wife, and struggles with the decision of whether to continue to work on the case or whether to return to Canada.<ref name=Threat>{{Cite journal|journal=Art Threat|author=Amanda McCuaig|date=September 11, 2012|title=She Has a Name leaves you breathless: Play on human trafficking touches without playing the guilt card|url=http://artthreat.net/2012/09/she-has-a-name-fringe/|accessdate=September 18, 2012}}</ref> In order to depict this tension, Jason and Ali communicate via Skype, represented on stage by two laptop computers placed back-to-back with Jason and Ali standing on either side facing one another. The two argue, but their interactions demonstrate the kind of love that Number 18 can only dream of.<ref name=Anna/> In the 2012 cross-Canada tour, a torn picture of Number 18's family remained on stage as scenery to emphasize what the character has lost. This picture took the form of a painted curtain held over a geometric floor pattern and depicted the family as tired, poor, and living in a shack.<ref name=Preachy/> Lana Michelin of the ''Red Deer Advocate'' said the most emotionally gripping scene was the one in which the voices cause Number 18 to recall the face of her dead father.<ref name=Lana/>  Anna Borowiecki of the ''St. Albert Gazette'' called the play a story of "fallible people who find strength in each other under the worst conditions".<ref name=Anna/>
[[File:She Has a Name 2011 - Embrace.jpg|thumb|alt=A photograph of a man wearing a blue dress shirt and blue jeans and looking into the eyes of a woman wearing a brown shirt and a blue jean skirt|[[Aaron Krogman]] portrayed both Jason and the pimp in the premiere, and stated that "both characters are struggling with power and how they use it".]]

Denise Wong, the [[List of people from Calgary|Calgarian]] actor who portrayed Number 18 in the premiere,<ref name=Advocate/> said that the play was about the [[human condition]].<ref name=Fast/> Evelyn Chew, the [[List of people from Vancouver|Vancouverite]] actor who took over the role for the 2012 tour, said that the play is intense because it unabashedly deals with human trafficking, and builds in intensity to its climax.<ref name=Chronicle/> Sienna Howell-Holden, who played Mama in the premiere and the 2012 tour, said that many audience members had not been previously familiar with 21st-century human trafficking.<ref name=Ignite>{{Cite journal|title=Where is God at the Fringe?|journal=[[CFEQ-FM]]|date=July 19, 2012}}</ref><ref name=CFUV/> The character of Mama calls attention to the fact that poverty in the Third World fuels sex trafficking.<ref name=Lana/> Stephen Waldschmidt said he hoped that the play will educate Canadians about human trafficking and motivate them to act on what they learn,<ref name=Strathmore/> thereby turning them into [[Abolitionism#Contemporary abolitionism|contemporary abolitionists]].<ref name=Returns/> He also said he hoped that the play will put a face on the million women and children sold into sexual slavery each year.<ref>{{cite web|publisher=[[CKOM]]|author=Stephanie Froese|date=April 21, 2012|title=She Has a Name puts face to sexual slavery in Saskatoon|url=http://www.newstalk650.com/story/she-has-name-puts-face-sexual-slavery-saskatoon/53480|accessdate=July 27, 2012}}</ref> Because of the play's heavy themes, producers of the first performances issued an advisory for parents.<ref name=Strathmore/> Waldschmidt also stressed the amount of action in the play<ref name=Returns/> and said that if the play was a film, it would receive a [[Motion Picture Association of America film rating system|PG-13 rating]]<ref name=Strathmore/> and would be billed a [[Thriller (genre)|thriller]].<ref name=Fast/> He also said it was difficult to stage a play that is inherently sexual and extremely violent in nature without making it feel pornographic.<ref name=Gauntlet/> Waldschmidt said that he wanted to stage ''She Has a Name'' partially to show how horrible human trafficking is and partially because the play is so theatrically gripping.<ref name=Advocate/>

The ''Country Sunrise News'' stated that the drama has a fast pace.<ref name=Sunrise/> Mallory Clarkson of the London Community News argued that, while ''She Has a Name'' is an emotional play, there are lighter moments where audience members can laugh.<ref name=Community>{{Cite journal|journal=London Community News|title=Sex trafficking highlighted in She Has a Name, playing July 12<U+2013>13 at the Aeolian|author=Mallory Clarkson|date=July 11, 2012|url=http://www.londoncommunitynews.com/2012/07/sex-trafficking-highlighted-in-she-has-a-name-playing-july-12-13-at-the-aeolian/|accessdate=July 26, 2012}}</ref> Similarly, Lana Michelin of the ''Red Deer Advocate'' asserted that the play's sporadic humourous points maintain the audience's engagement with the story so they do not become numb to the play's emotional pulls.<ref name=Advocate/> Kooman stated that he tried to write the play in a way that would shock audiences without disturbing them to the point that they would not recommend it to friends.<ref name=Playwright/> Marlo Campbell, a writer for ''[[Uptown (newspaper)|Uptown]]'', said that the play critiques masculine egotism and Western heroism through the character of Jason.<ref name=Uptown/> Lana Michelin of the ''Red Deer Advocate'' disagreed, stating that Jason never lapses into self-importance.<ref name=Lana/> Aaron Krogman, who portrayed Jason and the pimp in the play's premiere, said, "there is a thin line between Jason and the pimp&nbsp;...&nbsp;both characters are struggling with power and how they use it".<ref name=Standard/> Waldschmidt stated that the doubling of this role is intended to remind audiences that there are Canadians who are perpetrators of human trafficking<ref name=Project/> and that it "is not just somebody else's problem over there&nbsp;...&nbsp;but that it's us, and it's in our country and in our backyard and in our suburbs".<ref name=CFUV/> Jason has in this way been considered an everyman.<ref name=Plank>{{Cite journal|journal=Plank Magazine|author=Lisa Barrett|title=She Has A Name|date=September 8, 2012 |url=http://plankmagazine.com/review/she-has-name|accessdate=September 19, 2012}}</ref> One critic said that the play's Bangkok setting allows Canadians to easily disassociate from the issue.<ref name=Mennonite/> Liz Nicholls of the ''Edmonton Journal'' wrote that the pimp character "represents the ruthless spirit of pure human greed".<ref name=Nicholls/> Stephen Pederson of ''[[The Chronicle Herald]]'' called the play a combination of idealism, realism, and lyricism.<ref name=Preachy>{{Cite journal|journal=[[The Chronicle Herald]]|author=Stephen Pedersen|title=Preachy tone blunts power of She Has a Name|date=July 5, 2012|url=http://thechronicleherald.ca/artslife/113898-preachy-tone-blunts-power-of-she-has-a-name|accessdate=August 1, 2012}}</ref> Dustin Wiebe of the ''Mennonite Brethren Herald'' wrote that the play shows "the darker side of man<U+2019>s desire for control" by presenting Number 18 as having been stripped of her humanity.<ref name=Mennonite>{{Cite journal|journal=Mennonite Brethren Herald|author=Dustin Wiebe|title=A unsettling look into human trafficking: She Has a Name|url=http://www.mbconf.ca/home/products_and_services/resources/publications/mb_herald/september_2012/crosscurrents/current_play/|accessdate=September 20, 2012}}</ref> The disaster that concludes the play is [[Foreshadowing|foreshadowed]] throughout;<ref name=CBC>{{cite news|publisher=[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]]|date=July 21, 2012|author=Anna Lazowski|title=She Has a Name |url=http://www.cbc.ca/manitoba/scene/fringe/2012/07/she-has-a-name.html|accessdate=July 28, 2012}}</ref> the play both starts and ends with a depiction of the reality of contemporary slavery.<ref name=Winnipeg/>

==Critical response==
{{main|Critical response to She Has a Name}}
